%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% The Financial Analysis Process %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% 
\section{The Financial Analysis Process}
Due to the complex nature of financial analysis and the substantial amount of data a analyst should clarify purpose and context and clearly understand the following:
\begin{itemize}
  \item What is the purpose of the analysis? What questions will this analysis answer?
  \item What level of detail will be required to accomplish this purpose?
  \item What data are available for the analysis?
  \item What are the factors or relationships that will influence the analysis?
  \item What are the analytical limitations, and will these limitations potentially impair the analysis?
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\

Here is a overview of the financial statement analysis framework: \\
\hfill \\
\begin{tabular}{p{4cm} p{5cm} p{5cm}}
  \textbf{Phase} & \textbf{Sources of Information} & \textbf{Output} \\
  \hline
  1. Articulate the purpose and context of the analysis. & \(\bullet\) The nature of the analyst's function, such as evaluating and equity or debt investment or issuing a credit rating. & \(\bullet\) Statement of the purpose or objective of analysis. \\
    & \(\bullet\) Communication with client or supervisor on needs and concerns. & \(\bullet\) A list (written or unwritten) of specific questions to be answered by the analysis. \\
    & \(\bullet\) Institutional guidelines related to developing specific work product. & \(\bullet\) Nature and content of report to be provided. \\
    &   & \(\bullet\) Timetable and budgeted resources for completion. \\
  \hline
  2. Collect Data & \(\bullet\) Financial statements, other financial data, questionnaires, and industry/economic data. & \(\bullet\)Organized financial statements. \\
     & \(\bullet\) Discussions with management, suppliers, customers, and competitors. & \(\bullet\) Financial data tables. \\
     & \(\bullet\) Company site visits (e.g., to production facilities or retail stores). & \(\bullet\) Completed questionnaires, if applicable. \\
  \hline
  3. Process Data & \(\bullet\) Data from previous phase. & \(\bullet\) Adjusted financial statements. \\
    &   & \(\bullet\) Common-size statements. \\
    &   & \(\bullet\) Ratios and graphs. \\
    &   & \(\bullet\) Forecasts. \\
  \hline
  4. Analyze/interpret the processed data. & \(\bullet\) Input data as well as processed data. & \(\bullet\) Analytical results. \\
  \hline
  5. Develop and communicate conclusions and recommendations. & \(\bullet\) Analytical results and previous reports. & \(\bullet\) Analytical report answering questions posed in Phase 1. \\
    & \(\bullet\) Institutional guidelines for published reports. & \(\bullet\) Recommendation regarding the purpose of the analysis, such as whether to make an investment or grant credit. \\
  \hline
  6. Follow up. & \(\bullet\) Information gathered periodically repeating above steps as necessary to determine whether changes to holdings or recommendations are necessary. & \(\bullet\) Updated reports and recommendations. \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
\hfill \\
An analyst must be able to understand the "why" behind the numbers and ratios, not just what the numbers and ratios are. \\
\hfill \\


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Analysis Tools and Techniques %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% 
\section{Analysis Tools and Techniques}
We are going to cover four main types of tools: ratios, common-size analysis, graphs, and regression analysis. \\
\hfill \\

\subsection{Ratios}
One of the major tools for analysis are financial ratios. Ratios provide insight into the following: \\
\hfill \\
\begin{itemize}
  \item Microeconomic relationships within a company that help analysts project earnings and free cash flow.
  \item A company's financial flexibility, or ability to obtain the cash required to grow and meet its obligations, even if unexpected circumstances develop.
  \item The managements ability.
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\
There are also limitations to ratio analysis:
\hfill \\
\begin{itemize}
  \item \emph{The homogeneity of a company's operating activities}. Companies may have divisions operating in many different industries. This can make it difficult to find comparable industry ratios to use for comparison purposes.
  \item \emph{The need to determine whether the results of the ratio analysis are consistent}. One set of ratios may indicate a problem, whereas another set may prove that the potential problem is only short term in nature.
  \item \emph{The need to use judgment}. 
  \item \emph{The use of alternative accounting methods}. Some important accounting considerations include the following:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item FIFO vs. LIFO vs. Average Cost inventory valuation (IFRS no longer allow LIFO).
    \item Cost or equity methods of accounting for unconsolidated affiliates.
    \item Straight line or accelerated methods of depreciation.
    \item Capital or operating lease treatment.
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\
Some ratios can be retrieved from databases such as Bloomberg, Baseline, FactSet, or Thomson Reuters. \\
\hfill \\

\subsection{Common-Size Analysis}
Common-size analysis involves expressing financial data, including entire financial statements, in relation to a single financial statement item, or base. Items most frequently used for the bases are total assets or revenue. In essence, common-size analysis creates a ratio between every financial statement item and the base item. \\
\hfill \\
It is most common when analyzing the balance sheet to divide each item by the same period's total assets and expressing the result as a percentage to highlight the composition of the balance sheet. This allows the analyst to compare changes in percentages of line items between time periods. \\
\hfill \\
Common-size analysis of the income statement divides each income statement item by revenue (or sometimes by total assets). \\
\hfill \\
Cross-sectional analysis (sometimes called "relative analysis") compares a specific metric for one company with the same metric for another company or group of companies allowing for comparison even though the companies might be of significantly different sizes or operate in different currencies. \\
\hfill \\
Trend analysis is the process of looking through financial statements and ratios and identifying whether or not important metrics are improving or deteriorating. Trend analysis provides important information about historical performance and growth and can be of great assistance as a planning and forecasting tool for management and analysts. \\
\hfill \\
Trend data can be compared across different financial statements (duh!). \\
\hfill \\

\subsection{The Use of Graphs as an Analytical Tool}
Stacked column graphs are good for showing relative changes between multiple variables (e.g. inventory, receivables, investments, cash, fixed assets net of depreciation). They are also important when the composition and amounts, as well as their change over time are all important. \\
\hfill \\
Pie graphs are used to show composition of a total value. \\
\hfill \\
Line graphs are useful when the focus is on the change in amount for a limited number of items over a relatively longer time period. \\
\hfill \\

\subsection{Regression Analysis}
In statistics, regression analysis includes any techniques for modeling and analyzing several variables, when the focus is on the relationship between a dependent variable and one or more independent variables. More specifically, regression analysis helps us understand how the typical value of the dependent variable changes when any one of the independent variables is varied, while the other independent variables are held fixed. Most commonly, regression analysis estimates the conditional expectation of the dependent variable given the independent variables â€” that is, the average value of the dependent variable when the independent variables are held fixed. Less commonly, the focus is on a quantile, or other location parameter of the conditional distribution of the dependent variable given the independent variables. In all cases, the estimation target is a function of the independent variables called the regression function. In regression analysis, it is also of interest to characterize the variation of the dependent variable around the regression function, which can be described by a probability distribution. \\
\hfill \\
Regression analysis is widely used for prediction (including forecasting of time-series data). Use of regression analysis for prediction has substantial overlap with the field of machine learning. Regression analysis is also used to understand which among the independent variables are related to the dependent variable, and to explore the forms of these relationships. In restricted circumstances, regression analysis can be used to infer causal relationships between the independent and dependent variables. \\
\hfill \\
A large body of techniques for carrying out regression analysis has been developed. Familiar methods such as linear regression and ordinary least squares regression are parametric, in that the regression function is defined in terms of a finite number of unknown parameters that are estimated from the data. Nonparametric regression refers to techniques that allow the regression function to lie in a specified set of functions, which may be infinite-dimensional. \\
\hfill \\


