\section{Common Ratios Used in Financial Analysis}
There are five main categories of financial ratios. \\

\begin{tabular}{l p{9cm}}
  \textbf{Category} & \textbf{Description} \\
  \hline 
  Activity      & \textbf{Activity ratios} measure how efficiently a company performs day-to-day tasks, such as collection of receivables and management of inventory. \\
  Liquidity     & \textbf{Liquidity ratios} measure the company's ability to meet its short-term obligations. \\
  Solvency      & \textbf{Solvency ratios} measure a company's ability to meet long-term obligations. Subsets of these ratios are also known as "leverage" and "long-term debt" ratios. \\
  Profitability & \textbf{Profitability ratios} measure the company's ability to generate profitable sales from its resources (assets).  \\
  Valuation     & \textbf{Valuation ratios} measure the quantity of an asset or flow (e.g. earnings) associated with ownership of a specified claim (e.g. share of ownership). \\
\end{tabular}
\hfill \\

\subsection{Interpretation and Context}
An analyst should evaluate financial ratios based on the following: \\
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \emph{Company goals and strategy.} Actual ratios can be compared with company objectives to determine whether objectives are being attained and whether the results are consistent with the company's strategy.
  \item \emph{Industry norms (cross-sectional analysis)}. A company can be compared with others in its industry by relation its financial ratios to industry norms or to a subset of the companies in an industry. When industry norms are used to make judgments, care must be taken because:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item Many ratios are industry specific, and not all ratios are important to all industries.
    \item Companies may have several different lines of business. This will cause aggregate financial ratios to be distorted. It is better to examine industry-specific ratios by lines of business. 
    \item Differences in accounting methods used by companies can distort financial ratios. 
    \item Differences in corporate strategies can affect certain financial ratios.
  \end{itemize}
  \item \emph{Economic conditions} For cyclical companies, financial ratios tend to improve when the economy is strong and weaken during recessions. Therefore, financial ratios should be examined in light of the current phase of the business cycle. 
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Activity Ratios}
Also known as \textbf{asset utilization ratios} and \textbf{operating efficiency ratios}. \\
\begin{tabular}{p{4cm} p{10cm}}
  \hline
  \textbf{Inventory Turnover}                  & Costs of Goods Sold / Average Inventory \\
    & Indicates the resources (money) tied up in inventory (e.g. the carrying costs) and can, therefore, be used to indicate inventory management effectiveness. The higher the ratio, the shorter the period that inventory is held (resulting in lower DOH as well). This should be benchmarked against industry norms.  \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Days of Inventory on Hand (DOH)}     & Number of Days in Period / Inventory Turnover \\
    & The number of days worth of inventory the company keeps. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Receivables Turnover}                & Revenue / Accounts Receivable \\
    & A relatively high ratio (resulting in a low DSO) might indicate highly efficient credit and collection. Although it is is too high it's credit/collection might be to stringent and causing business to go elsewhere. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Days of Sales Outstanding (DSO)}     & Number of Days In Period / Receivables Turnover \\
    & The number of DSO represents the elapsed time between a sale and cash collection. Although limiting the numerator to sales made on credit would be more accurate, credit sales information is not available to a analyst.  \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Payables Turnover}                   & Purchases / Average Trade Payables \\
    &  Represents how many times a company pays off its creditors per year. If this ratio is high it might mean that a company is not making full use of its credit (alternatively it might mean that a company is taking advantage of early pay discounts). A low payables turnover ratio might indicate that a company is having trouble meeting its obligations or alternatively exploiting lenient supplier terms. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Number of Days of Payables}          & Number of Days in Period / Payables \\
    &  Represents the average number of days that a company takes to pay its suppliers. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Working Capital Turnover}            & Revenue / Average Working Capital \\
    & Working capital is current assets - current liabilities. This ratios details how efficiently a company generates revenue with its working capital. The higher the ratio the greater the efficiency. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Fixed Asset Turnover}                & Revenue / Average Net Fixed Assets \\
    & Measures how efficiently the company generates revenues from its investments in fixed assets. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Total Asset Turnover}                & Revenue / Average Total Assets \\
    &  Measures a company's overall ability to generate revenues with a given level of assets. Is used as a measure of efficiency. \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}

\subsection{Liquidity Ratios}
Liquidity ratios are focused largely on cash flows, and are used to measure a company's ability to meet its short-term obligations. \\
\hfill \\

\begin{tabular}{p{4cm} p{7cm}}
  \hline
  \textbf{Current Ratio}                & Current Assets / Current Liabilities \\
    &  A higher ratio indicates a higher level of liquidity. A value of 1.0 indicates that the book value of its current assets exactly equals the book value of current liabilities. A lower ratio indicates a lower level of liquidity, implying a greater reliance on operating cash flow and outside financing to meet short-term obligations. Liquidity affects the company's capacity to take on debt. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Quick Ratio}                  & Cash + Short-term marketable investments + Receivables / Current Liabilities \\
    & More conservative than the current ratio because it only includes more liquid current assets. This removes everything except what in the numerator of the equation from the current assets. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Cash Ratio}                   & Cash + Short-term marketable investments / Current Liabilities \\
    & Represents a reliable measure of a individual entity's liquidity in a crisis situation. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Defensive Interval Ratio}     & Cash + Short-term marketable investments + Receivables / Daily Cash Expenditures \\
    &  Indicates how long a company can continue to pay its expenses from its existing liquid assets without receiving any additional cash inflow. A defensive interval ratio of 50 would indicate that a company can continue to pay its operating expenses for 50 days before running out of quick assets, assuming no additional cash inflows. \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
\hfill \\

Another measure of liquidity is the \textbf{cash conversation cycle} which is a financial metric not in ratio form, that measures the length of time required for a company to go from cash (invested in operations) to cash received (as a result of its operations). During this period of time, the company need to finance its investment in operations through other sources (e.g. debt and or equity). \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Cash Conversion Cycle (Net operating Cycle)} = DOH - DSO - Number of Days of Payables.
\hfill \\

\subsection{Solvency Ratios}
Solvency refers to a company's ability to meet its long-term debt obligations. \\
\hfill \\

The following are examples of \emph{debt-ratios}: \\
\hfill \\

\begin{tabular}{p{4cm} p{7cm}}
  \hline
  \textbf{Debt-To-Assets Ratio (Total Debt Ratio)} & Total Debt / Total Assets \\
    & Measure the percentage of total assets financed with debt. For example a Debt-To-Assets ratio of .6 means 60\% of the company's assets are financed with debt. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Debt-To-Capital Ratio} & Total Debt / Total Debt + Total Shareholders' Equity \\
    & Measure the percentage of a company's capital that is represented by debt. A higher ratio represents more financial risk and thus indicates weaker solvency. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Debt-To-Equity Ratio} & Total Debt / Total Shareholders' Equity \\
    & Measures the amount of debt capital to equity capital. A higher ratio means weaker solvency. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Financial Leverage Ratio} & Average Total Assets / Average Total Equity \\
    & Also known as the "leverage ratio" this ratio measure the amount of total assets supported for each one money unit of equity. A ratio of 3 would mean that for every one dollar in equity supports three dollars in total assets. The higher the financial leverage ratio, the more leveraged the company is in the sense of using debt and other liabilities to finance assets. \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
\hfill \\
\hfill \\
 
The following are examples of \emph{coverage-ratios}: \\
\begin{tabular}{p{4cm} p{7cm}}
  \hline
  \textbf{Interest Coverage} & EBIT / Interest Payments \\
    & Measure the number of times that a company's EBIT could cover its interest payments. A higher ratio indicates stronger solvency, offering greater assurance that the company can service its debt from it operating earnings. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Fixed Charge Coverage} & EBIT + Lease Payments / Interest Payments + Lease Payments \\
    & This ratio relates fixed charges, or obligations, to the cash flow generated by the company. It measures the number of times a company's earnings (before interest, taxes, and lease payments) can cover the company's interest and lease payments. A higher ratio indicates stronger solvency. This ratio is sometimes used as an indication of the quality of the preferred dividend, with a higher ratio indicating a more secure preferred dividend. \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}

\subsection{Profitability Ratios}
Many analysts focus on the profitability ratios as the key focus on their analytical efforts. Many consider profitability ratios to be a good measure of a company's management. Check on the income statement for most of these. \\
\hfill \\
\hfill \\

The following ratios are considered \emph{return on sales} profitability ratios: \\
\begin{tabular}{p{4cm} p{7cm}}
  \hline
  \textbf{Gross Profit Margin} & Gross Profit / Revenue \\
    & Gross profit margin indicates the percentage of revenue available to cover operating and other expenditures. If it is higher it indicates some combination of higher product pricing and lower product cost. Can be used to access competitive advantage of products. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Operating Profit Margin} & Operating Income / Revenue \\
    & Operating profit is calculated as gross profit margin minus operating costs. So a operating margin increasing greater than a gross margin can indicate improvements in controlling operating costs, such as administrative overheads. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Pretax Profit Margin} & EBT (earnings before tax but after interest) / Revenue \\
    & Pretax income (also known as earnings before tax) is calculated as operating profit minus interest, so this ratio reflects the effects on profitability of leverage and other (non-operating) income and expenses. If a company's pretax margin is rising primarily as a result of increasing non-operating income, the analyst should evaluate whether this increase reflects a deliberate change in a company's business focus and, therefore, the likelihood that the increase will continue. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Net Profit Margin} & Net Income / Revenue \\
    & Used to offer a view of the company's future potential profitability. Not a measure of efficiency. Tells you how much profit is generated from one dollar in sales. \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
\hfill \\
\hfill \\

The following ratios are considered \emph{return on investment} profitability ratios: \\
\begin{tabular}{p{4cm} p{7cm}}
  \hline
  \textbf{Operating ROA} & Operating Income / Average Total Assets \\
    &  This is the "Operating Income or EBIT / Average Total Assets" method mentioned below. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{ROA (return on assets)} & Net Income / Average Total Assets \\
    & The higher the ratio, the more income is generated by a given level of assets. Most databases compute this ratio as "Net Income / Average Total Assets". Some analyst prefer to add back the interest expanse yielding "Net Income + Interest Expense (1 - Tax Rate) / Average Total Assets". Also some analysts compute ROA on pre-interest and pretax basis yielding "Operating Income or EBIT / Average Total Assets". \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Return on Total Capital} & EBIT / Short- and long-term debt and equity \\
    & Measures the profit that a company earned on all of the capital that it employs (short-term debt, long-term debt, and equity). \\
  \hline
  \textbf{ROE} & Net Income / Average Total Equity \\
    & Includes minority equity, preferred equity, and common equity. It is a measure of return on equity. \\
  \hline
  \textbf{Return on Common Equity} & Net Income - Preferred Dividends / Average Common Equity \\
    &  Much like ROE mentioned above only return on common equity is only concerned with common equity. \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
\hfill \\
\hfill \\

\subsection{DuPont Analysis: The Decomposition of ROE}
ROE = Net Income / Average Shareholders' Equity \\
\hfill \\
ROE = Net Income / Average Shareholders' Equity \\
    = (Net Income / Average Total Assets) * (Average Total Assets / Average Shareholder Equity) \\
\hfill \\
Which can be expressed as: \\
\hfill \\
ROE = ROA * Leverage \\
\hfill \\
Using the above equation you can determine the trend in ROE to figure out whether the increase/decrease from ROE is a function of ROA or leverage. \\
\hfill \\
Just as ROE can be decomposed we can then further decompose ROE by decomposing ROA: \\
\hfill \\
ROE = (Net Income / Average Total Assets) = (Net Income / Revenue) * (Revenue / Average Total Assets) * (Average Total Assets / Average Shareholder Equity) \\
\hfill \\
This can be interpreted as:  
\hfill \\
ROE = Net Profit Margin * Asset Turnover * Leverage \\
\hfill \\
To separate the effects of taxes an interest, we can further decompose the net profit margin and write: \\
\hfill \\
(Net Income / Average Shareholders' Equity) = (Net Income / EBT) * (EBT / EBIT) * (EBIT / Revenue) * (Revenue / Average Total Assets) * (Average Total Assets / Average Shareholders' Equity) \\
\hfill \\
which can be interpreted as: \\
\hfill \\
ROE = Tax burden * Interest Burden * EBIT Margin * Asset Turnover * Leverage \\
\hfill \\
NOTE: The interest burden can be described as either (EBT / EBIT) or as (EBT / Operating Income). Using operating income allows for measurement of both the effect of interest expense and non-operating income. \\
\hfill \\

