NOTE: EBITDA stands for Earnings Before Interest, Tax, Depreciation, and Amortization. \\
\hfill \\
\begin{tabular}{l p{4cm} p{4cm}}
    & \textbf{Numerator} & \textbf{Denominator} \\
  \hline
  \multicolumn{3}{l}{\textbf{Dividend-Related Quantities}} \\
  \hline
  Dividend payout ratio & Common share dividends & Net income attributable to common shares \\
  Retention rate (b) & Net income attributable to common shares - Common Share Dividends & Net income attributable to common shares \\
  Sustainable Growth Rate & b * ROE & \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
\hfill \\
The dividend payout ratio measures the percentage of earnings that the company pays out as dividends to shareholders. The amount of dividends per share tends to be relatively fixed because any reduction in dividends has been shown to result in a disproportionately large reduction in share price. Because dividend amounts are relatively fixed, the dividend payout ratio tends to fluctuate with earnings. Optimal dividend policy, similar to optimal capital structure, has been examined in academic research and continues to be a topic of significant interest in corporate finance. \\
\hfill \\
The retention rate is the complement of the payout ratio (1 - payout ratio). Whereas the payout ratio measures the percentage of earnings that a company pays out as dividends, the retention rate is the percentage of earnings that the company retains. \\
\hfill \\
A company's sustainable growth rate is viewed as a function of its profitability (measured as ROE) and its ability to finance itself from internally generated funds (measured as the retention rate). A higher ROE and a higher retention rate result in a higher sustainable growth rate. This calculation can be used to estimate a company's growth rate, a factor commonly used in equity valuation. \\
\hfill \\

