\section{Business and Geographic Segments}
Under IAS 14 (Segment Reporting), disclosures are required for reportable segments. U.S. GAAP is similar to IFRS but less detailed. One noticeable omission under U.S. GAAP is the disclosure of segment liabilities. \\
\hfill \\
A reportable segment is defined as a business or geographical segment where both of the following apply:
\begin{itemize}
  \item The majority (greater than 50 percent) of its revenue is earned externally.
  \item Its income from sales, segment results, or assets is greater than or equal to 10 percent of the appropriate total amount of all segments.
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\
For each primary segment, the following should be disclosed: \\
\begin{itemize}
  \item Segment revenue, distinguishing between revenue to external customers and revenue from other segments.
  \item Segment result (segment revenue minus segment expenses).
  \item Carrying amount of segment assets.
  \item Segment liabilities.
  \item Cost of property, plant, and equipment, and intangible assets acquired.
  \item Depreciation and amortization expense.
  \item Other non-cash expense.
  \item Share of the net profit or loss of an investment accounted for under the equity method.
  \item Reconciliation between the information of reportable segments and the consolidated financial statements in terms of segment revenue, result, assets, and liabilities.
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\

For each secondary segment, the following should be disclosed:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Revenue from external customers.
  \item Carrying amount of segment assets.
  \item Cost of property, plant, and equipment, and intangible assets acquired.
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\

Other required disclosures are as follows:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Revenue of any segment whereby the external revenue of the segment is greater than or equal to 10 percent of company revenue but that is not a reportable segment (because a majority of its revenue is from internal transfers).
  \item Basis of pricing inter-segment transfers.
  \item Changes in segment accounting policies.
  \item Types of products and services in each business segment.
  \item Composition of each geographical segment.
\end{itemize}
\hfill \\

\subsection{Segment Ratios}
Based on the limited segment information that companies are required to present, a variety of useful ratios can be computed: \\
\begin{tabular}{l p{9cm}}
  \textbf{Segment Margin}      & Segment Profit (loss) / Segment Revenue \\
  \textbf{Segment Turnover}    & Segment Revenue / Segment Assets \\
  \textbf{Segment ROA}         & Segment Profit (loss) / Segment Assets \\
  \textbf{Segment Debt Ratio}  & Segment Liabilities / Segment Assets \\
\end{tabular}


\section{Model Building and Forecasting}
There are a lot of techniques used in modeling financial forecasts. Here are several:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Sensitivity Analysis}: Also known as the "what if" analysis. This shows a range of outcomes as specific assumptions are changed. This in turn could influence financing needs or investment in fixed assets.
  \item \textbf{Scenario Analysis}: Scenario analysis shows the changes in key financial quantities that result from given (economic) events, such as the loss of customers, the loss of a supply source, or a catastrophic event. If the list of events is mutually exclusive and exhaustive and the events can be assigned probabilities, the analyst can evaluate not only the range of outcomes but also standard statistical measures such as the mean and median value for various quantities of interest.
  \item \textbf{Simulation}: A computer-generated sensitivity or scenario analysis based on probability models for the factors that drive outcomes. Each event or possible outcome is assigned a probability. Multiple scenarios are then run using the probability factors assigned to the possible values of a variable.
\end{itemize}


